  "prompt": "Can you be allergic to meat and fish?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible to have allergies to both meat and fish. While fish allergies are more commonly recognized, meat allergies, although less common, can also occur. \n\n1. **Fish Allergy**: This is one of the more common food allergies and can cause reactions ranging from mild symptoms (like hives or gastrointestinal discomfort) to severe anaphylaxis. It is typically associated with certain species of fish, and individuals with fish allergies may also react to shellfish.\n\n2. **Meat Allergy**: One well-known type is related to a component called alpha-gal (galactose-\u03b1-1,3-galactose), which can cause allergic reactions to red meat (such as beef, lamb, and pork) after a person has been bitten by a lone star tick. This condition is sometimes called \"alpha-gal syndrome.\" Other individuals might experience allergies to poultry or other types of meat, although this is rarer.\n\nIf you suspect you have a food allergy to meat or fish, it's important to consult with a healthcare professional for proper evaluation and testing. Avoiding the allergens and being cautious with food choices is crucial to managing these allergies.",
